
1. What is the difference between normal input widgets and form widgets in Streamlit?

Normal widgets trigger immediate script re-execution on user interaction. Form widgets batch inputs until explicit form_submit_button() activation.

| Aspect            | Normal Widgets                        | Form Widgets              |
| ----------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Rerun Trigger     | Every change (slider drag,  edit)     | Submit button only        |
| Execution Cost    | N× reruns (N widgets)                 | Single batch execution    |
| State Persistence | Individual widget state               | Atomic form state         |
| Use Case          | Real-time previews                    | Data validation workflows |

Execution Trace:

❌ Normal: slider→rerun→→rerun→checkbox→rerun (3× compute)
✅ Form:   fill→fill→fill→submit→single rerun (1× compute)



2. Why are forms useful in collecting multiple inputs?

Forms eliminate intermediate states, ensuring data consistency and validation completeness:

Real-world Example: User Registration
❌ Normal widgets: Partial data processed on each keystroke
✅ Form: Complete dataset validated atomically

Performance Gain: 70-90% reduction in compute cycles
UX Gain: No flickering/jumpy UI during data entry

